  . This form of the surname is common mainly in Ireland and Scotland."],"variants":[{"name":"Whyde","meanings":["English: perhaps an altered form of   Whyte   or   Hyde  ."]},{"name":"White","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>white</i>, <i>wit</i> (Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’), hence a nickname for someone with white hair or a pale complexion. In some cases it is perhaps from a Middle English survival of the Old English personal name <i>Hwīta</i>, a short form of names in <i>Hwīt-</i> (from <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’). The name may also be topographic, referring to someone who lived by a bend or curve in a river or road (from Old English <i>wiht</i> ‘bend’), the source of the placename of Great Whyte in Ramsey, Huntingdonshire (compare   Wight  ). This name is also a variant of   Wight  . The surname <i>White</i> is also very common among African Americans.","Irish and Scottish: adopted for any of several Irish and Scottish Gaelic names based on <i>bán</i> ‘white, fair’ (see   Bain   1,   McElwain  ) or <i>fionn</i> ‘fair’ (see   Finn   1). The English surname has been Gaelicized in Ireland as <b>de Faoite</b>.","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘white’, for example German   Weiss  , French   Blanc  , Polish <b>Białas</b> (see   Bialas  ), Slovenian   Belec  , or any other synonymous Slavic surname beginning with <i>Bel-</i>, <i>Bev-</i>, <i>Biel-</i> or <i>Bil-</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Whyte was born in 1430, in Farnham, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1469, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1430–1469":"1430–1469","1438–1513":"1438–1513","1469":"1469","1513":"1513","1430":"1430","1438":"1438","Farnham England":"Farnham, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},